<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
The specific epithet refers to the flowers of this new species that are green throughout the flowering period, differing from those of all other known 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="Saxifraga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saxifraga subsp. sect." order="Saxifragales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Irregulares" species="kegangii" subSpecies="sect.">Saxifraga sect. Irregulares</taxonomicName>
species. The Chinese name is given as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“绿花虎耳草”">&quot;绿花虎耳草&quot;</normalizedToken>
(lǜ 
<normalizedToken originalValue="huā">hua</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="hǔ">hǔ</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="ěr">er</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="cǎo">cǎo</normalizedToken>
), referring to the greenish petals of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
In a two year personal observation of this new species in its native range, Guangxi. Guilin City (Luo Dexuan, pers. comm.), 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. viridiflora" order="Saxifragales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridiflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">S. viridiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
